content.description: No real crux, just a nice balancy, traverse upwards.
content.protection: Use the same rope you did for tires and gas, and Michael's Mysery.
content.location: Starts to the left of the cave, you work your way diagonally across the face pulling up over the triangle of rock from Michael's mysery.

content.description: This climb follows the line up the right side of the face, over a block about 10 feet off the ground. Pulling up over the block is the crux.   Its a nice warm up, or nice climb for a beginner.
content.location: Obvious line on the right side of the face.

content.description: Climb up to the right side of the cave and go to the right of the flake and straight up.
The climb is sustained. It feels good.
content.location: This face is directly over the cave in the middle of the face.  Start on the right side of the cave and move over the cave and then pull yourself up on small ledges, and then out on the overhanging triangular block to the left once you are past the ledges.

content.description: The crux is the two dynamic moves.  I learned this from a guy named Matt who was with the Cornell College climbing club.  Its greeeaaat!
content.location: Start to the left of the cave and work your way up and to the right, staying under the flake. Get an undercling and then launch up to the Hueco, use it as an undercling and launch again for a second Hueco.

content.description: The crux is pulling the crack at the top. Its deceptively off balance.
content.location: Its the farthest left route on the face. Go up the messy place to the left, and then pull the crack at the top.

content.description: It is a highly featured piece of rock about 30 feet tall.
